h exceeds recent investments in\u00a0&quot;fact&quot; or\u00a0&quot;fiction&quot; to\u00a0consider multiple ways of knowing and seeing. Readings will draw from multiple disciplines and forms, and will address a wide range of practices across the 20th and 21st centuries, multiple geographic locations, and give special attention to how\u00a0speculation might\u00a0offer new insight into post-and decolonial, feminist, diasporic, queer, or 'global' art histories."}, {"name": "Teaching Method", "value": "Seminar"}, {"name": "Evaluation Method", "value": "Paper, finalProject, finalWriting assignmentsStudents will hand in weekly response papers and a final research paper or project."}, {"name": "Class Materials (Required)", "value": "Rachel Kusher, The Flamethrowers, Scribner, 2013, 1439142017; Siri Hustvedt, The Blazing World, Simon and Schuster, 2014, 1476747245. All other readings are available as PDF files via Canvas."}], "lmod": "2/8/17 6:40 PM (CT)", "subject": "ART_HIST"}]
